==Service history==
[[File:Ottoman Fleet 1914.png|thumb|Silhouettes of the major warships of the Ottoman Navy in 1914; the ''Peyk-i Şevket''-class is the fourth ship in the second row]]

Both ships saw extensive service with the Ottoman fleet over the course of the decade following their arrival in November 1907. They took part in the first fleet maneuver conducted by the fleet in over twenty years in 1909.<ref>Langensiepen & Güleryüz, p. 14</ref> Neither ship saw action during the [[Italo-Turkish War]] of 1911&ndash;12, as ''Peyk-i Şevket'' had been interned at British-controlled [[Suez]] at the outbreak of war,<ref>Langensiepen & Güleryüz, p. 25</ref> and ''Berk-i Satvet'' was stationed with the reserve fleet in the [[Sea of Marmara]], which did not risk confrontation with the significantly stronger Italian fleet.<ref>Beehler, p. 12</ref> Both ships saw combat during the [[First Balkan War]] in 1913, primarily in supporting Ottoman forces ashore in [[East Thrace]]. The ships provided gunfire support to the Ottoman army holding the [[Çatalca]] line in defense of the capital at [[Constantinople]].<ref>Erickson, pp. 288–289</ref> ''Berk-i Satvet'' also took part in two brief skirmishes with the [[Greek Navy]].<ref>Langensiepen & Güleryüz, p. 24</ref>

The Ottoman Empire joined [[World War I]] in November 1914; ''Peyk-i Şevket'' and ''Berk-i Satvet'' primarily operated in the [[Black Sea]] against the Russian [[Black Sea Fleet]]. They frequently patrolled the Ottoman coast, particularly off the [[Bosporus]], and escorted convoys to western [[Anatolia]]. On one of these convoy operations in January 1915, ''Berk-i Satvet'' struck a mine that wrecked her stern. She was towed back to Constantinople and repaired,<ref>Langensiepen & Güleryüz, p. 46</ref> returning to service in 1918.<ref name=LG149/> ''Peyk-i Şevket'' returned to the Sea of Marmara during the [[Dardanelles Campaign]] in 1915, where she carried munitions to the defending Ottoman forces. On 6 August, she was torpedoed by the British [[submarine]] {{HMS|E11}} and was badly damaged,<ref>Langensiepen & Güleryüz, pp. 38–39</ref> with repairs lasting until 1917.<ref name=LG149/> Both ships were used as convoy escorts in the Black Sea in the final year of the war.<ref>Langensiepen & Güleryüz, p. 54</ref>

The two cruisers were retained by the new [[Turkish Navy]] following the end of the [[Turkish War of Independence]] in 1923, and their names were shortened to ''Peyk'' and ''Berk''. Lengthy overhauls followed, in 1924&ndash;5 for ''Berk'' and 1927&ndash;9 for ''Peyk''. They were modernized a decade later, in 1936&ndash;8 for ''Peyk'' and 1937&ndash;9 for ''Berk''. The ships remained in service until 1944, when they were stricken from the [[naval register]] and laid up at the [[Gölcük Naval Shipyard]] before being scrapped after 1953.<ref name=GG392/><ref name=LG149/>

